{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_jupiter_ver01/data/sn90050267/00513688763/1908031401/0419.xml":{"full_text":"THE DAILi GUARD\nBy Th*\nBATESVILLE PBIMTIKQ COMPAMY.\nGeo. H. Trevathan, Manager.\nB. L. GIVENS President\nTHEO. MAXFIELU. ...Vice President\nDirector*.\nT. B. Padgett, E. L. Givens, S. A. Hail,\nJohn y Wolf, Theodore Maxfield.\nEntered at the Postottice at Batesville,\nArk., as second-class matter.\nPublished Every Afternoon Except\nSunday\nANNOUNCEMENTS.\nThe Guard is authorized to an-\nBounce the following candidates, sub\nject to the action of the Democratic\nprimaries:\nFor Congress\u2014\nW. A. OLDFIELD.\nM. J. MANNING.\nFor Railroad Commissioner\u2014\nG. W. BELLAMY.\nJOHN W. CROCKETT.\nFor Representative\u2014\nW. M. THOMPSON.\nJ. L. BROWN.\nI. J. MATHENY.\nA. G. GRAY.\nFor County Judge\u2014\nCUL. L. PEARCE.\nA. J. CRAIG.\nJOHN T. THARP.\nFor Circuit Clerk\u2014\nGEORGE BEVENS.\nARMIE HODGES.\nFor County Clerk\u2014\nALBERT SIMS.\nFor Sheriff\u2014\nALBERT L. DUNLAP.\nJ. A. KANEASTEL.\nFor Collector\u2014\nWINFRED T. GRAY.\nWILL MIMS.\nJ. T. POWELL.\nFor Assessor\u2014\nC. M. FLINN.\nELBERT L. JERNIGAN.\nW. F. DANIELS.\ni CHAS. E. LENEHAN.\nDEXTER LINDSEY.\nFor Treasurer\nFRANKLIN PERRIN.\nFor Surveyor.\nOSCAR WARREN.\nfor Coroner\u2014\nR. L. FLINN.\nM. C. LONG.\nJ. R. CHURCHWELL.\nFor Road Overseer, Ruddell township.\nW. L. WILKINS.\nY. M. ENGLES.\nE. HILL.\nRoad Overseer, Gainsboro township.\nF. M. THOMPSON.\nRoad Overseer, White River townshin.\nJ. C. HUDDLESTON.\nJOHN ASHLEY.\nR. P. WHALEY.\n\u2019'or Road Overseer, Washington\nTownship,\nWm. RYAN.\nMagness Township,\nW. E. GRISHAM.\nBlack River Township,\nW. A. PARR.\nAshlev Township,\nW. L. OTTINGER.\nFor Constable, Ruddell Township.\nR. L. PATTERSON.\nW. C. MEACHUM.\nFor Road Overseer, Greenbrier Town\nship\u2014\nTHOS. 11. ELMS.\nW. D. CHURCHWELL.\nRoad Overseer. Ashley Township\u2014\nG. W. COMER.\nFor Road Overseer, Gainsboro town\nship\u2014\nTHOMAS MORRIS.\nFOR CITY OFFICES.\nFor Mavor.\nDENE H. COLEMAN.\nELMER HINKLE.\nR. P. WEAVER.\nFor City Recorder\u2014\nT. ALBERT.\nFor City Treasurer\u2014\nW. A. MITCHELL.\nFor Marshal\u2014\nR. R. CASE.\nE. F. DECAMP.\nS. C. MANKIN.\nNOTICE.\nOwing to circumstances which had\nnothing to do with the quality of the\nland, I find myself with one thousand\nacres of the best land in Oil Trough\nBottom for rent. Will rent for cash,\nor for part of crop; or, if I can get\nsome good men who can furnish sat\nisfactory reference, I will put up\nland, teams and tools against their\nlabor, on shares. I will advance all\nnecessary supplies for making the\ncrop, and if you have team and no\nfeed, I will furnish feed.\nApply by letter or in person to\nD. A. Yancey, Dunnington, Ark.\nU Z* A IL LLL\nBATESVILLE DRUG COMPANY. Agents\nReports from Rogers state that the\nprospects are bright for a bountiful\nfruit crop in that section.\nGov. Haskell has signed the bill\npassed by the Oklahoma legislature\nplacing all mines in that state under\ncontrol of the state inspector.\nChas. F. King, the New York fin\nancier and implacable enemy of Tom\nLawson, of \u201cfrenzied finance\u201d fame,\nhas been adjudged a bankrupt.\nSaharah Temple of Shriners made\na pilgrimage to Fort Smith this week\nand held a ceremonial session, at\nwhich a class of twenty-five were\ninitiated.\nGov. Beckham of Kentucky, recent\nly defeated for the United States Sen\nate by Mr. Bradly, a republican, has\nannounced that he will never again\naccept office.\nGuisseppe Alia, the Italian anarch\nist, who murdered Father Leo Hein\nrichs while the latter was administer\ning sacrament in a Denver church\nthree weeks ago, has been sentenced\nto be hanged July 18th.\nIra L. Lipe, a former employe of\nthis office, was married Tuesday to\nMiss Maggie Lewis of Mayflower.\nMr. Lipe is a member of the Log\nCabin Democrat force of Conway.\nThe Guard offers congratulations.\nSupt. Pitcock of the state peniten\ntiary says the cotton acreage this\nyear on the state farm will be in\ncreased about 400 acres, and that al\ntogether the state will cultivate about\n3,000 acres in cotton.\nJ. T. Owen, a visitor to Hot\nSprings from St. Louis, jumped from\nan out-going Iron Mountain train and\nsustained painful injuries. The man\nwas found several hours after the ac\ncident, and upon examination he was\nfound to be in a demented condition.\nSilas Lingg, formerly a clerk in\nthe postoffice at Helena, was convict\ned in federal court in that city of\nrobbing the mails and given a sen\ntence of one year in the penitentiary.\nLingg, who is only 22 years of age,\nand from a prominent family, entered\na plea of guilty.\nEd .1. O'Connor was shot and killed\nat Eudora by Willie Maule, his broth\n'er-in-law. O'Connor was only released\nfrom the penitentiary recently, where\nhe served a term for assaulting his\nbrother-in-law. O\u2019Connor went to the\nhome of Maule and assaulted him\nwith a razor, when Maule grabbed a\nrevolver and shot O\u2019Connor dead.\nNotice of a ten per cent cut in the\nwages of Massachusetts cotton mill\nemployes has been posted in seven of\nthe largest mills in Lowell. Nearly\n25,000 operatives will be effected by\nthe reduction. The manufacturers\nstate that the business outlook is\nmost discouraging, and that the in\ndustry, north and south, is depressed.\nPOISONING CATTLE.\nThe \u201cnight riders\u201d of Kentucky\nhave resorted to another method of\nlawlessness, and are now poisoning\nthe cattle of those who meet their\ndisapproval.\nNOTICE TO TEACHERS.\nNotice is hereby given that there\nwill be a public examination at Bates\nville, Ark., on Thursday and Friday,\nthe 19th and 20th days of March,\n1908, to ascertain the professional\nqualifications of all persons desiring\nto teach in the public schools of Ar\nkansas within the limits of Independ\nence county. The examination will\nbegin promptly at 8:30 a. m. and\neach applicant is requested to be\npresent at that hour.\nGiven under my hand, this, the\n24th day of February, 1908.\nSIDNEY PICKENS,\nCounty Examiner.\nWORMOLOGY\nshould be studied by every parent. If\nyour child is nervous, fretful, starts\nin its sleep, is pasty faced, has rings\nunder its eyes, always seems hungry,\nis not gaining weight, you can be\nsure the trouble is worms. White\u2019s\nCream Vermifuge is an absolute cure\nfor worms. Is it\u2019s ofn purgative.\nSold by E. R. Goodwin, Druggist\nPROPOSED AMENDMENT\nTO THE CONSTITUTION OF THE STATE\nOF ARKANSAS.\nNotice is hereby given that the fol\nlowing joint resolution, proposing an\namendment to the State Constitution,\nwas passed by the General Assembly\nat its regular session of 1907, and\nthat the same will be submitted to\nhe electors of the State at the next\ngeneral election, to be held Monday,\nSeptember 14, 1908, for adoption or\nrejection, viz.:\nPROPOSED AMENDMENT NO. 9.\n\u201cEvery male citizen of the United\nStates or male person who has de\nlared his intention of becoming a\nitizen of the same, of the age of\nwenty-one years, who has resided in\nhe state twelve months, in the coun\ny six months, and in the precinct,\ntown or ward one month, next pre\neding any election at which he may\npropose to vote, except such persons\nas may for the commission of some\nfelony be deprived of the right to\nvote by law passed by the General\nAssembly ana who shall exhibit a\npoll tax receipt or other evidence that\nhe has paid his poll tax at the time\nof collecting taxes next preceding\nuch election, shall be allowed to vote\nat any election in the State of Ar\nkansas. Provided, That persons who\nmake satisfactory proof that they\nave attained the age of twenty-one\nyears since the time of assessing\naxes next preceding said election and\nossessed tne other necessary quali\ncations, shall be permitted to vote,\nnd provided further, that the said\nax receipt shall be so marked by\nated stamp or written endorsement\ny the judges of election to whom it\nlay be first presented as to prevent\nhe holder thereof from voting more\nhan once at any election.\u2019\u2019\nThe above resolution was filed in\nhe office of the Secretary of State on\nApril 27, 1907.\nEach elector may vote for or\ngainst the above amendment.\nWitness my official signature this\n4th day of February, 1908.\nO. C. LUDWIG,,\nSecretary of State.\n(Seal.)\nNotice is hereby given that the fol\nlowing joint resolution, proposing an\nmendment to the State Constitution,\nwas passed by the General Assembly\nat its regular session of 1907, and\nthat the same will be submitted to\nhe electors of the State at the next\ngeneral election, to be held Monday.\nSeptember 14, 1908, for adoption or\nrejection.\nPROPOSED AMENDMENT NO. 10.\n\u201cThat Section 1 of Article 1(5 of\nf the Constitution of the State of\nArkansas be amended so as to read\ns follows:\nArticle 1(5. Section 1. Neither\nthe State nor any city, town, county\nor other municipality in this State\nshall ever loan its credit for any pur\nose whatever, nor shall any county,\nity, town or municipality ever issue\nny interest bearing evidences of in\nebtedness, except such bonds as may\nbe authorized by law to provide for\nthe construction and maintenance of\n\u00fcblic highways in counties, cities and\nowns, and the construction, pur\nchase and maintenance of. public im\nprovements of a general nature in\ncities and towns.\nProvided, That bonds or evidences\nf indebtedness shall not be issued for\nan amount more: than ten per cent of\nhe assessed valuation of all real and\npersosal property in city, town or\ncounty proposing to issue same.\nSuch bonds shall not bear a great\ner rate of interest than five per cent\nper annum, and in order to provide\nfor the payment of such bonds and\ninterest, a special tax not to exceed\nthree mills pn the dollar, in addition\nto the rate of taxation, now author\nized, may be levied by said counties,\ncities and towns.\nAnd the State shall never issue any\ninterest bearing treasury warrants or\nscrip.\u201d\nThe above resolution was filed in\nthe office of the Secretary of State\non May 23, 1907.\nEach elector may vote for or\nagainst the above amendment.\nWitness my official signature this\n24th day of February, 1908.\nO. C. LUDWIG,\n(Seal.) Secretary Os State.\nNO USE TO DIE.\n\u201cI have found out that there is no\nuse to die of lung trouble as long as\nyou can get Dr. King\u2019s New Discov\nery,\u201d says Mrs. J. P. White of Rush\nboro, Pa. \u201cI would not be alive to\nday only for that wonderful medicine.\nIt loosens up a cough auicker than\nanything else, and cures lung disease\neven after the case is pronounced\nhopeless.\u201d This most reliable remedy\nfor coughs and colds, la grippe, asth\nma, bronchitis and hoarseness, is sold\nunder guarantee at E. R. Goodwin\u2019s\ndrug store. 50c and sl. Trial bot\ntle free.\nNOTICE.\nNotice is hereby given that the an\nnual election of directors of the\nBatesville Board of Trade will be held\nat the office of the secretary in the\nBank of Batesville building on\nTUESDAY, MARCH 17th, 1908.\nNine directors are to be elected.\nPolls open at 9 a. m. and close at 4\np. m. M. C. Weaver, Prest.\nBy A. A. Webber, Secretary.\nBatesville, Ark., February 17, 1908.\nBEST HEALER IN THE WORLD.\nRev. F. Starbird of East Raymond,\nMaine, says: \u201cI have used Buck\nlen\u2019s Arnica Salve for several years\non my old army wound, and other\nI Farm Seeds and Feed.i\n\n\n\nWe are now receiving the largest Stock of Farm\nJ Seeds ever brought to Batesville, consisting of Two\nStraight Cars of Clover, Timothy, Alfalfa, Millet,\nJ Johnson Grass, Etc., and one car of Seed Oats. We\nare also getting in two Cars of Feed and a car of\nSash ano Doors. J\nOUR NEW LOCATION j\nw\nJ Is at the Albright and Ramsey building on Main Street J\nopposite Barnett Bros, where our immense stock can J\nbe seen.\nJ With the largest stcck to select from, the very\nbest quality of seeds and the lowest prices we are\nJ better prepared than ever to serve our friends.\nJ\nI Talley Lumber and Feed Co.\nGO-CARTS\nEntirely New Style Gear, y\nEasy Springs\u2014as Easy for\na baby of one week as I\nfor a child of four years.\nPrices $2.50 to 14.00\nWeekly Payments. C\nA. L. CROUCH I\nSecond Hand furniture Bought, Sold and Exchanged I\nEUGENE R. GOODWIN I\nDruggist I\nPure and Fresh Drugs, Chemicals, Etc. I\nThree Licensed Pharmacists. Every man in the I\nstore is registered under the Laws of Arkansas I\nA full line of Toilet Articles I\nFine Perfume and Stationery I\nYOUR PATRONAGE SOLICITED I\nEUGENE R. GOODW/Al\nobstinate sores, and find it the best\nhealer in the world. I use it, too,\nwith great success in my veterinary\nbusiness.\u2019\u2019 Price 25c at Goodwin\u2019s\ndrug store.\nLAME SHOULDER.\nWhether resulting from a sprain\nor from rheumatic pains, there is\nnothing so good for a lame shoulder\nas Chamberlain\u2019s Pain Balm. Ap\nply it freely and rub the parts vig\norously at each application and a\nquick cure is certain. For sale by\nE. R. Goodwin, Druggist.\nBuy the American Poultry and\nRabbit Fence, which is the best on\nthe market. Barnett Bros. Merc. Co.,\nBatesville, Ark,\nIl's Risky_fusiiifss\nto have careless workmen install im\nperfect plumbing materials in your\nhome, store or shop\u2014so many things\nare apt to happen to make sueh dam\nage that repairing and replacing will\ncost far more than the difference in\ncost between first-class and second\nclass plumbing. See ue about the\nhighest class known.\nL. H. PASCOE co.\nBATESVILLE, ARK.","height":"18090","width":"11751"}}
